Siemens per centimeter,

00:36:21.110 --> 00:36:41.620
the conductivity of pure water is
less than ten to the minus seven.

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:29.140
It's some number times ten to the
minus eight Siemens per centimeter.

00:36:29.140 --> 00:36:33.280
So, what's happening? When we
dissolve silver chloride,

00:36:33.280 --> 00:36:37.420
we are adding, this is the same as
doping. We are adding charge

00:36:37.420 --> 00:36:41.560
carriers, only instead of adding
holes to the valence band,

00:36:41.560 --> 00:36:45.710
or electrons to the conduction band,
that's not going to help us because

00:36:45.710 --> 00:36:49.850
water isn't a metal.
Water is capable of dissolving ions.

00:36:49.850 --> 00:37:10.166
So, we're going to make it an ionic
conductor by injecting carriers.

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:38.000
The more silver chloride we dissolve,
the greater the number of carriers.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:42.000
The greater the number of carriers,
the greater the conductivity. So,

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:46.000
by measuring conductivity as a
function of concentration,

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:50.000
we can determine if we are
dissolving the silver chloride,

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:54.000
as opposed to we keep adding it and
it just sinks to the bottom.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:58.000
So, let's look here. What we find
is as we add silver chloride,

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:02.000
the conductivity of the solution
rises up to a maximum value at

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:06.000
around ten to the minus five moles
of silver chloride per

00:37:06.000 --> 00:37:29.830
liter of solution.
So, that would be a concentration of

00:37:29.830 --> 00:37:33.490
10 to the minus five molar.
And then, what happens? We keep

00:37:33.490 --> 00:37:37.160
adding silver chloride,
but the conductivity doesn't change.

00:37:37.160 --> 00:37:40.830
So, what do you think is happening
if you could stare at the beaker?

00:37:40.830 --> 00:37:44.490
You could see the silver chloride
just falling to the bottom.

00:37:44.490 --> 00:37:48.160
So, the knee in the curve indicates
that we've reached saturation

00:37:48.160 --> 00:38:07.753
solubility. So that's good.
So, we have evidence to support.

00:37:32.500 --> 00:37:37.500
Now, we can then compare the
solubility with the solubility

00:37:37.500 --> 00:37:42.500
product in the following manner.
We can say that the relationship

00:37:42.500 --> 00:37:47.500
between the saturation solubility is
really equal to the concentration of

00:37:47.500 --> 00:37:52.500
silver chloride dissolved,
which Arrhenius has told us is

00:37:52.500 --> 00:37:57.500
really the concentration of silver
ion, which is equal to the

00:37:57.500 --> 00:38:22.380
concentration of chloride ion.
All of these are the same.

00:38:22.380 --> 00:38:27.160
And so, with a little bit of
algebra, we can show them that the

00:38:27.160 --> 00:38:31.940
relationship between this and Ksp is
- since the concentration of silver

00:38:31.940 --> 00:38:36.720
equals the concentration of chloride,
then we can take Ksp to the one half

00:38:36.720 --> 00:38:41.490
will then equal the C star,
the saturation solubility. And,

00:38:41.490 --> 00:38:46.270
for silver chloride, it turns out
that the product,

00:38:46.270 --> 00:38:51.050
the solubility product,
is 1.8 times ten to the minus ten,

00:38:51.050 --> 00:38:55.830
which then means that the saturation
solubility for silver chloride is

00:38:55.830 --> 00:39:00.610
the square root of that,
which is about 1.3 times ten to the

00:39:00.610 --> 00:39:04.840
minus five.
And, sure enough,

00:39:04.840 --> 00:39:08.530
that's what you see on this plot.
You see that somewhere just a

00:39:08.530 --> 00:39:12.230
little bit higher than ten to the
minus five molar,

00:39:12.230 --> 00:39:15.920
the plot has flattened out.
But now, let's look at the more

00:39:15.920 --> 00:39:19.610
interesting case and put the
solubility product to work and ask

00:39:19.610 --> 00:39:23.300
ourselves, what happens if we add
silver chloride not to pure water,

00:39:23.300 --> 00:39:43.933
but to a solution that contains
already some other dissolved salt.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:32.110
Is that going to have an impact on
the amount of silver chloride we can

00:39:32.110 --> 00:39:37.220
dissolve? So,
let's give a specific example,

00:39:37.220 --> 00:39:42.330
and a specific example is add silver
chloride to a solution already

00:39:42.330 --> 00:39:47.440
containing sodium chloride.
I'm going to add silver chloride to

00:39:47.440 --> 00:39:51.590
a solution of 0.1 molar NaCl.
So, I already have chloride ion

00:39:51.590 --> 00:39:54.790
present. See,
this is interesting.

00:39:54.790 --> 00:39:57.990
If I said that, instead of adding
silver chloride to pure water,

00:39:57.990 --> 00:40:01.190
I'm going to add silver chloride to
water that already contains some

00:40:01.190 --> 00:40:04.390
silver chloride,
you say, well, that's obvious.

00:40:04.390 --> 00:40:07.590
If it contains some silver chloride,
I can't put as much in as I

00:40:07.590 --> 00:40:10.790
otherwise could.
But now I'm going to say,

00:40:10.790 --> 00:40:13.990
it's not silver chloride. It's
sodium chloride.

00:40:13.990 --> 00:40:17.190
Does the presence of sodium
chloride have any impact on the

00:40:17.190 --> 00:40:20.390
dissolution of silver chloride?
So, again, we'll look Arrhenius'

00:40:20.390 --> 00:40:24.900
theory of electrolytic dissociation.
So, silver chloride will dissociate

00:40:24.900 --> 00:40:30.720
and go into solution as silver
cation and chloride anion.

00:40:30.720 --> 00:40:36.540
And, sodium chloride is present as
sodium ion and chloride ion.

00:40:36.540 --> 00:40:42.360
So, we've got now, note here
multiple sources of chloride ion.

00:40:42.360 --> 00:40:48.180
We're getting some chloride ion
from silver chloride,

00:40:48.180 --> 00:41:05.626
and we get some chloride ion from
sodium chloride.

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:38.000
So, the consequence of that is that
I know I can no longer assume that

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:42.000
the concentration of silver ion
equals the concentration of chloride

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:46.000
ion. That's no longer the case
because I've got some chloride ion

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:50.000
that came from sodium chloride.
So, that's a problem. That's a

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:54.000
problem. So, what do I do?
I'm going to try to find the

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:58.000
saturation solubility of silver
chloride under these

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:22.400
new circumstances.
So, I'm going to go back to my

00:41:22.400 --> 00:41:27.200
solubility product,
Ksp. And, Ksp is going to equal the

00:41:27.200 --> 00:41:31.990
product of the silver ion
concentration times the

00:41:31.990 --> 00:41:36.790
concentration of the chloride ion.
And, I can take a stab at what this

00:41:36.790 --> 00:41:41.590
is. I told that this is on the
order of 0.1 molar.

00:41:41.590 --> 00:41:46.390
And, we saw that in the case of
pure silver chloride,

00:41:46.390 --> 00:41:51.190
it's ten to the minus five molar.
It's about four orders of magnitude

00:41:51.190 --> 00:42:09.446
lower even when we have
full dissociation here.

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:41.500
So, I'm going to assume that ten to
the minus one molar is so much

00:41:41.500 --> 00:41:47.000
greater than ten to the minus five
molar, which is what we got in pure

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:52.500
silver chloride that I'm going to
neglect the contribution of chloride

00:41:52.500 --> 00:41:58.000
ion from silver chloride,
and say that the concentration of

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:03.500
chloride ion is simply equal to 0.
because 0.1 is so much greater than

00:42:03.500 --> 00:42:09.000
what is left over from the
previous calculation.

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:34.390
And now, I can still make the
connection between the dissolution

00:42:34.390 --> 00:42:39.790
of silver chloride salt,
and the concentration of silver ion.

00:42:39.790 --> 00:42:45.190
That still exists as one to one.
So, this will then represent C of

00:42:45.190 --> 00:42:50.590
silver chloride times 0.
. And, that's equal to this 1.

00:42:50.590 --> 00:43:08.913
times ten to the minus, what is it,
ten to the minus ten.

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:42.000
So, I can solve for the
concentration of silver chloride,

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:48.000
and that gives me 1.8 times ten to
the minus nine molar.

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:54.000
So, the presence of the chloride
from sodium has had a tremendous

00:42:54.000 --> 00:43:00.000
repressive effect on the dissolution
of silver chloride.

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:25.060
This is called the common ion effect
because I have a common ion from

00:43:25.060 --> 00:43:30.130
both solutes, and one influences the
solubility of the other: common ion

00:43:30.130 --> 00:43:35.190
effect. And, we can use the common
ion effect to our advantage.

00:43:35.190 --> 00:43:40.260
If I want to process something in
order to cause precipitation of very,

00:43:40.260 --> 00:43:45.330
very fine particles,
I can load a solution with one

00:43:45.330 --> 00:43:50.390
solute, introduce a second solute,
and trigger the precipitation, and

00:43:50.390 --> 00:43:55.460
in doing so, control particle size,
and the shape, and thereby prepare a

00:43:55.460 --> 00:44:00.180
material for subsequent processing.
In fact, you can use this.

00:44:00.180 --> 00:44:04.540
If you want to determine if you've
got water that's been chlorinated,

00:44:04.540 --> 00:44:08.900
simple thing you can do: if you go
back to that table 8.

00:44:08.900 --> 00:44:13.270
, you'll know that silver nitrate
has a very, very high solubility in

00:44:13.270 --> 00:44:17.630
water. So, I introduce silver
nitrate into water,

00:44:17.630 --> 00:44:36.593
and the question is,
is there any chlorine present?

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:07.000
And, if there's any chlorine present,
we know that the saturation

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:12.000
solubility of silver chloride is ten
to the minus five molar.

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:17.000
What will happen is if you've got
chlorinated water,

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:22.000
and you add silver nitrate,
you will see a shower of very,

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:27.000
very fine, white powder, which is
the silver chloride.

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:32.000
So, this is a very good test for
residual chlorination.

